page.title: 09FORESTRY CONTINUED
page.content: Delamere/Eddisbury {FORESRTY CONTINUED On the western edge of the forest where there are marl deposits a richer flora including chickweed & giant horsetail can be found. Two of the wetter mosses have been declared SITES OF SPECIAL SCIENTIFIC INTEREST. There is one sizeable wet floating sphagnum bog with cranberry & the insectivorous common sundew.A variety of mosses & liverworts are associated with the damp wet areas.The forest is rich in fungal flora both edible & poisonous. The forest is also of great interest for the birds it supports. Tits, thrushes & finches,nuthatches,wood- peckers(green & greater spotted),& kestrels & sparrow hawks.Tawney owls are often heard at night while Little owls hunt by day.
